{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17411398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17411398"},"attributes":{"position":11,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14878"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477819"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:06:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:06:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14878"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1260986"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T06:24:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:02:58+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":13,"questionsAnswered":0,"marksTotal":0,"marksAttainable":0,"marksAttempted":0,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T06:25:33+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0,"questionsCorrect":0,"marksCorrect":0},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"14878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14878"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.43,0.06,0.2,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7569"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112119"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7569"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14878"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94184"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3750"},{"type":"tags","id":"6625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18510"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45944"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112119"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of increasing fatigue and pallor. Her parent noticed yellow discolouration of her eyes yesterday. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 105/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. She has marked pallor and scleral icterus. Her spleen is palpable 3 cm below the costal margin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 65 g/L (115-145)\u003Cbr /\u003EMean cell volume: 92 fL (75-95)\u003Cbr /\u003EWhite cell count: 12 x 10^9/L (4.5-13.5)\u003Cbr /\u003EPlatelet count: 350 x 10^9/L (150-450)\u003Cbr /\u003EReticulocyte count: 15% (0.5-2.5)\u003Cbr /\u003ETotal bilirubin: 45 \u03bcmol/L (3-20)\u003Cbr /\u003EDirect bilirubin: 8 \u03bcmol/L (0-5)\u003Cbr /\u003ELactate dehydrogenase: 450 U/L (120-300)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Flow cytometry","Direct antiglobulin test","Bone marrow aspiration","Haemoglobin electrophoresis","Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase level"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of autoimmune haemolytic anaemia (AIHA), specifically warm AIHA. The clinical triad of pallor, jaundice, and splenomegaly, along with laboratory evidence of haemolysis (elevated reticulocytes, unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia, and raised lactate dehydrogenase) are characteristic findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect antiglobulin test\u003C/strong\u003E (DAT, also known as direct Coombs test) is the most appropriate next investigation. It detects the presence of antibodies or complement bound to red blood cells and is the key diagnostic test for immune-mediated haemolysis. A positive DAT confirms the diagnosis of AIHA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone marrow aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if there were concerns about bone marrow failure or malignancy. However, the elevated reticulocyte count indicates an appropriate bone marrow response to haemolysis, making this investigation unnecessary at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlow cytometry\u003C/strong\u003E would be useful if there were concerns about paroxysmal nocturnal haemoglobinuria or other membrane defects. However, the presentation is more consistent with immune-mediated haemolysis. Flow cytometry could also be used to diagnose hereditary spherocytosis by demonstrating reduced eosin-5-maleimide binding. However, hereditary spherocytosis typically presents with a positive family history, chronic haemolysis from infancy, and spherocytes on blood film. The acute presentation in this previously well child makes an acquired process more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase\u003C/strong\u003E level testing would be appropriate if investigating hereditary haemolytic anaemia, particularly in the context of oxidant exposure. However, the acute presentation and clinical features are more suggestive of an immune-mediated process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemoglobin electrophoresis\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose haemoglobinopathies, which typically present with chronic haemolysis from infancy. The acute presentation and normal mean cell volume make a haemoglobinopathy less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce AIHA is confirmed with a positive DAT, treatment typically involves corticosteroids (prednisolone) as first-line therapy. The response is usually rapid, with improvement in haemoglobin levels within 1-2 weeks. Some patients may require blood transfusion if severely symptomatic, though this can be challenging due to difficulty in cross-matching.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Direct antiglobulin test (DAT) is the key investigation for diagnosing immune-mediated haemolysis","Warm autoimmune haemolytic anaemia typically presents with pallor, jaundice and splenomegaly in children","Initial treatment of warm autoimmune haemolytic anaemia is prednisolone"],"references":["Voulgaridou A, Kalfa TA. Autoimmune Hemolytic Anemia in the Pediatric Setting. J Clin Med. 2021 Jan 9;10(2):216. doi: 10.3390/jcm10020216. PMID: 33435309; PMCID: PMC7828053."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94184"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14878"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94184"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-25T16:39:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-25T16:40:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7569"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112119"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paedia